<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-495-848  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 495 848.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computers in Healthcare  June 1990 v11 n6 p39(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>National chains: why the experts were wrong. (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Murrie, Robert I.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>When the 1980s began, healthcare experts predicted that a smallnumber of national chains would dominate the hospital field by theyear 1990.andP;  But prospective payment systems (PPS) changed thearena for hospitals, turning them into competitive entitiesinstead of utility-style institutions.andP;  PPS brought about regionalclusters of hospitals, three to five facilities in a metropolitanarea that are able to capture a significant market share and sorealize economies of scale, improved quality of care, and have astronger negotiation position with third parties.andP;  One questionfacing clusters is that of how much to centralize and what toleave decentralized.andP;  Critical to the success of clusters are theability of technology and systems to adapt to changing needs andto consolidate clinical information across networks.andP;  Hospitalprofitability, falling in recent years, has begun to turn upward.andO;Clusters should allow hospitals to improve patient care.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     HospitalEconomics of ComputingMarket ShareHospital Information Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>